title: For Sale/Trade:  Unique Frommer Stop
postcontent:
For sale or trade is a Frommer Stop in 7.65(.32acp). From the serial number, this pistol appears to have been manufactured in 1921 in Hungary.
This particular pistol is interesting in that is has a Norwegian police “POLITI” marking. After the liberation of Norway in WWII, German soldiers surrendered all of their arms. Many of these surrendered weapons were 7.65mm pistols. After the war many of these pistols were inspected and pushed into service with the Norwegian police. Supposedly, from what I’ve read, only 55 Frommer stops were accepted by the Norwegians, and they were numbered 8001 to 8055. The Norwegian serial number on this pistol is 8007, making it the 7th Frommer accepted. It also has a strange "Sr" in a box on the trigger guard, which I have been unable to identify.
This is a very cool pistol that utilizes a long recoil action, where both the bolt and the barrel travel backwards together.
Overall, the pistol Is in ok shape. The metal has a grey-brown patina all over. There is some very light spotting in some areas. The bore looks to be in good shape. Magazine is not original and seems to be a reproduction.
I originally had some cycling issues with this pistol, but I replaced the bolt head and now it functions flawlessly. I'll includes the original bolt head just in case the buyer wants to tinker with it.
Given the rarity of these, I'm not sure what it's really worth, so I'm asking $700 or best offer.

I'm located in Fairfax city, but I make it down to Harrisonburg fairly often, and could possibly meet down that way.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1100 rounds  7.62x51/ .308 ammo for sale
postcontent: Prefer a local sale on ammo, but will ship with buyer paying the actual cost.I have:600 rounds of Israeli 7.62x51 ammo- reloadable.  Brass is like new. 500 rounds British L2A2 7.62x51 ammo- non-reloadable. Has superficial black discoloration from copper 2 oxide.  It's the result of copper's natural reaction with air.  It creates a coating, like bluing or parkerizing, that inhibits corrosion.  It's not like rust on steel that eats into and weakens the metal- this surface oxidation does not penetrate the brass.  Call an ammo manufacturer, ask for their metalurgical engineer, then ask them why they don't coat their brass to prevent copper oxide.  If brass contacting air makes brass unsafe, they'd coat it.  I've shot both the Israeli and British ammo and they both work great.  All 1100 rounds $550 or trade for guns
